        "title": "Manipulating a class list in a loop, while the condition iterates over that list",
        "body": "<p>Sorry if the title was unclear. I'm not exactly sure how to word it.<\/p>\n\n<p>So I have static Game class. This Game class contains multiple ArrayLists as class variables.<\/p>\n\n<p>My job is to reduce the Game as much as possible. To do this I have implemented a reduce(Game) function which performs the next reduction step.<\/p>\n\n<p>Of course, the reduce function edits the array lists stored under the Game class. For example, it will remove turns that are not needed.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have a reducable(Game) function that returns true if the game can be reduced more. The function iterates over the various moves and returns true if a move is not needed, false otherwise.<\/p>\n\n<p>The problem I am having, is that the reducable function is attempting to use/lookup moves that were deleted prior in the iterations.<\/p>\n\n<p>So for example if I try:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>while(reducable(game))\n     reduce(game);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I get an array index out of bounds error from reducable, because it is using the original array size and not the new size.<\/p>\n\n<p>If I depend on something such as input or a counter then it works fine<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>while(!scanner.nextLine().contains(\"stop\"))\n     reduce(game);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>However this is not a reasonable solution because I am trying to make it perform automatic and I will not know how many reductions are needed.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here is the base of my code being used<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public static void performReduction(Game game){\n    int i = 0;\n    while(reducable(game)){\n        reduce(game);\n    }\n\n}\npublic static boolean reducable(Game game){\n    for(int i = 0; i &lt; game.turns.get(0).size(); i++){\n        for(int j = 0; j &lt; game.turns.get(1).size(); j++){\n            if(notNeeded(....))\n                return true;\n        }\n    }\n    return false;\n}\npublic static boolean notNeeded(Game g, int p){\n        for(int i = 0; i &lt; game.turns.get(p).size(); i++){\n            for(int j = 0; j &lt; game.turns.get(p).size(); j++){\n                 if(....)\n                    return truel\n                }\n            }\n        return false;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The problem, more or less:\nThe reduce function removes information from the lists in Game. (ie. turns)\nThe conditional function that performs the while loop needs to iterate over these functions to determining if a reduction is possible.\nGives an out of bounds error for attempting to access list indices that are no longer there.<\/p>\n\n<p>I've tried using the reducable function as a class function, but that gave the same results. I've also tried having reduce return a Game instance, and using recursion but that also gave the same results.<\/p>\n\n<p>`<\/p>\n",
